almonds.name: Almonds
almonds.description: Raw almonds, a nutrient-dense tree nut rich in healthy monounsaturated fats, vitamin E, magnesium, and fiber. Excellent for heart health and blood sugar control.
healthBenefits: Rich in monounsaturated fats that lower LDL cholesterol and support cardiovascular health
High vitamin E content provides powerful antioxidant protection
Excellent magnesium source supports healthy blood pressure and blood sugar regulation
High fiber content promotes satiety and digestive health
Contains plant sterols that help block cholesterol absorption
Protein and healthy fats provide sustained energy without blood sugar spikes

nutritionContext.portionGuidance: A small handful (1 oz) makes an ideal snack. 2 servings per day fits well in most healthy eating patterns.
nutritionContext.preparationTips: Enjoy raw, lightly toasted, or as almond butter. Soak overnight to improve digestibility and nutrient absorption.
nutritionContext.pairingRecommendations: Pair with fresh fruit, add to oatmeal or yogurt, blend into smoothies, or use as a salad topping for added crunch and nutrition.
nutritionContext.timingConsiderations: Excellent as a mid-morning or afternoon snack to prevent blood sugar crashes. The protein and fat combination provides 3-4 hours of sustained energy.

walnuts_english.name: Walnuts
walnuts_english.description: English walnuts, the only nut rich in plant-based omega-3 fatty acids (ALA). Exceptional for brain health, heart health, and reducing inflammation.
healthBenefits: Highest plant-based omega-3 (ALA) content of any nut, supporting brain and heart health
Rich in polyphenolic antioxidants that protect against oxidative stress and inflammation
Supports cognitive function and may reduce age-related cognitive decline
Helps improve blood vessel function and lower blood pressure
May reduce risk of certain cancers through anti-inflammatory compounds
Supports healthy gut microbiome diversity

nutritionContext.portionGuidance: 1 oz (14 halves) daily provides optimal omega-3 benefits. Can consume up to 2 oz as part of a balanced diet.
nutritionContext.preparationTips: Best consumed raw to preserve delicate omega-3 fats. Store in refrigerator or freezer to prevent rancidity.
nutritionContext.pairingRecommendations: Add to salads, oatmeal, or yogurt. Blend into pesto or smoothies. Pair with dark leafy greens to enhance nutrient absorption.
nutritionContext.timingConsiderations: Excellent as an afternoon snack or post-workout to support brain function and reduce inflammation. The omega-3s are best absorbed with a meal containing some fat.

cashews.name: Cashews
cashews.description: Raw cashews, a creamy tree nut rich in copper, magnesium, and healthy monounsaturated fats. Supports bone health, immune function, and energy production.
healthBenefits: Exceptionally high copper content supports iron absorption and immune function
Rich in magnesium for bone health, energy production, and blood pressure regulation
Provides zinc and selenium to support immune system strength
Monounsaturated fats help lower LDL cholesterol
Contains iron to support healthy red blood cell formation
Vitamin K supports bone mineralization and blood clotting

nutritionContext.portionGuidance: 1 oz (18 cashews) is an ideal portion. Due to higher carb content compared to other nuts, limit to 1-2 servings daily if managing blood sugar.
nutritionContext.preparationTips: Enjoy raw, lightly roasted, or as cashew butter. Soak 2-4 hours to create creamy cashew cream for dairy-free recipes.
nutritionContext.pairingRecommendations: Blend into smoothies for creaminess, use in stir-fries, or make dairy-free cheese sauces. Pair with vitamin C-rich foods to enhance iron absorption.
nutritionContext.timingConsiderations: Good pre-workout snack for quick energy. The combination of carbs and healthy fats provides both immediate and sustained energy for 2-3 hours.

pistachios.name: Pistachios
pistachios.description: Raw pistachios, a colorful tree nut rich in protein, fiber, antioxidants, and B vitamins. Supports eye health, blood sugar control, and weight management.
healthBenefits: Highest protein and fiber content among common nuts, promoting satiety and weight management
Rich in lutein and zeaxanthin antioxidants that protect eye health and reduce macular degeneration risk
Excellent vitamin B6 source supports brain function and neurotransmitter production
High potassium-to-sodium ratio helps regulate blood pressure
Lower calorie density than most nuts supports portion control and weight management
Prebiotic fiber supports beneficial gut bacteria growth

nutritionContext.portionGuidance: 1 oz (49 kernels) provides satisfaction with fewer calories than other nuts. The act of shelling slows eating and increases mindfulness. Can enjoy 1-2 oz daily.
nutritionContext.preparationTips: Choose in-shell pistachios to slow consumption. Lightly roast to enhance flavor while preserving nutrients. Avoid heavily salted versions.
nutritionContext.pairingRecommendations: Add to salads, yogurt parfaits, or grain bowls. Use crushed pistachios as a coating for fish or chicken. Blend into pesto for vibrant color and flavor.
nutritionContext.timingConsiderations: Ideal afternoon snack to prevent overeating at dinner. The protein and fiber combination provides 3-4 hours of sustained energy and satiety.

pecans.name: Pecans
pecans.description: Raw pecans, a buttery tree nut exceptionally high in antioxidants, healthy fats, and minerals. Outstanding for heart health and reducing oxidative stress.
healthBenefits: Highest antioxidant content among all tree nuts, protecting against cellular damage
Rich in monounsaturated fats that lower LDL cholesterol and improve heart health
Excellent manganese source supports metabolism and antioxidant defenses
Very low net carbs make them ideal for ketogenic and low-carb diets
May help reduce post-meal blood sugar spikes and improve insulin sensitivity
High thiamin content supports energy metabolism and nervous system function

nutritionContext.portionGuidance: 1 oz (19 halves) provides rich satisfaction. Due to high fat content (good fats!), 1-1.5 oz daily is ideal for most people.
nutritionContext.preparationTips: Enjoy raw for maximum antioxidant preservation. Lightly toast to enhance buttery flavor. Store in refrigerator to prevent rancidity.
nutritionContext.pairingRecommendations: Add to salads, roasted vegetables, or oatmeal. Use in baking for natural sweetness and texture. Pair with dark chocolate for an antioxidant powerhouse.
nutritionContext.timingConsiderations: Excellent as a satisfying afternoon snack. The high fat content provides long-lasting satiety (4-5 hours), helping prevent evening overeating.

peanuts.name: Peanuts
peanuts.description: Raw peanuts, technically a legume but nutritionally similar to tree nuts. Rich in protein, niacin, folate, and resveratrol. Excellent for heart health and energy.
healthBenefits: Highest protein content among common nuts, supporting muscle maintenance and satiety
Exceptional niacin (vitamin B3) source supports energy metabolism and cellular health
Very high folate content supports cardiovascular health and cell division
Contains resveratrol, the same antioxidant found in red wine, with anti-aging properties
Rich in p-coumaric acid and other polyphenols that reduce oxidative stress
Supports healthy blood sugar regulation despite moderate carb content

nutritionContext.portionGuidance: 1 oz (28 peanuts) provides excellent protein and energy. Can consume 1-2 oz daily as part of a balanced diet. Choose dry-roasted or raw over oil-roasted for best nutrition.
nutritionContext.preparationTips: Enjoy raw, dry-roasted, or as natural peanut butter (no added oils or sugars). Avoid honey-roasted or heavily salted varieties.
nutritionContext.pairingRecommendations: Add to stir-fries, Thai-inspired dishes, or trail mix. Pair with vegetables for satisfying snacks. Combine with whole grain toast for complete protein.
nutritionContext.timingConsiderations: Excellent pre-workout snack (30-60 min before exercise) for sustained energy. Post-workout, the protein supports muscle recovery. As a snack, provides 3-4 hours of satiety.
